1
00:00:38,455 --> 00:00:43,544
ROSE: Doctor! Doctor, look out!
Doctor, he's going! Quick!

2
00:00:46,421 --> 00:00:48,423
DOCTOR: Where's he gone?
Do you see him?

3
00:00:48,507 --> 00:00:51,260
ROSE: There he is. Stop! No!
DOCTOR: Where is he?

4
00:00:51,343 --> 00:00:53,345
ROSE: Watch out!
DOCTOR: Where?

5
00:00:59,017 --> 00:01:01,186
(SNARLING)

6
00:01:26,378 --> 00:01:28,213
That's what it did, it went...

7
00:01:28,338 --> 00:01:29,923
(ROARING)

8
00:01:30,007 --> 00:01:33,385
And if you think
that was the most exciting day of my life,

9
00:01:33,468 --> 00:01:35,429
wait till you hear the rest.

10
00:01:35,512 --> 00:01:36,888
Oh, boy.

11
00:01:36,972 --> 00:01:39,224
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

12
00:02:14,968 --> 00:02:17,054
So there I was, with that thing going...

13
00:02:22,434 --> 00:02:27,147
Here, boy. Eat the food. Come on.
Look at the lovely food, isn't that nice?

14
00:02:27,230 --> 00:02:29,650
Isn't it? Yes, it is! Get out of here, quickly.

15
00:02:29,733 --> 00:02:31,943
(IN BABY TALK) That's a boy!
Who'd like a porky choppy, then?

16
00:02:32,069 --> 00:02:33,779
I said run!

17
00:02:33,862 --> 00:02:35,489
(SCREAMING)

18
00:02:37,991 --> 00:02:40,869
-Wrong one! You made it worse!
-You said blue.

19
00:02:40,952 --> 00:02:42,871
I said not blue!

20
00:02:45,749 --> 00:02:47,376
Hold on.

21
00:02:53,048 --> 00:02:55,175
(DOCTOR AND ROSE SCREAMING)

22
00:03:11,817 --> 00:03:13,402
Hold on.

23
00:03:14,653 --> 00:03:16,238
Don't I know you?

24
00:03:23,161 --> 00:03:25,205
(WHOOSHING)

25
00:03:27,290 --> 00:03:30,293
You can't imagine it, the Doctor's machine.

26
00:03:31,169 --> 00:03:35,257
The most beautiful sound in the world.

27
00:03:35,632 --> 00:03:40,637
That wasn't the first time I met the Doctor
and it certainly wasn't the last.

28
00:03:40,721 --> 00:03:42,013
Oh, no.

29
00:03:42,139 --> 00:03:46,101
I just put that bit at the beginning
because it's a brilliant opening.

30
00:03:46,184 --> 00:03:49,646
But this is the story of me

31
00:03:49,730 --> 00:03:53,400
and my encounters with alien life forms.

32
00:03:53,483 --> 00:03:58,989
But be warned!
Because it is gonna get scary.

33
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:02,075
I need a remote control zoom.

34
00:04:02,159 --> 00:04:05,662
I'm having to do that with a lean,
the scary. Anyway.

35
00:04:05,787 --> 00:04:10,834
But don't worry 'cause it's not just me
sitting here talking. Oh, no.

36
00:04:10,917 --> 00:04:14,463
-That's Ursula on camera.
-Hello.

37
00:04:14,546 --> 00:04:17,924
My good friend Ursula Blake
on my brand-new camera.

38
00:04:18,008 --> 00:04:22,387
That was my family home, down there.

39
00:04:22,512 --> 00:04:25,974
I did try
but there's two women live there now.

40
00:04:26,057 --> 00:04:28,935
They're a bit severe. So, never mind.

41
00:04:29,019 --> 00:04:34,107
But that is where it all started
"cause that's when I first met the Doctor.

42
00:04:36,818 --> 00:04:41,114
What was it?
I must've been three or four years old.

43
00:04:41,198 --> 00:04:44,618
Middle of the night I went downstairs,

44
00:04:44,701 --> 00:04:47,412
and there was this man.

45
00:04:52,876 --> 00:04:56,880
URSULA: So what happened? Elton?
Tell me, why was he there?

46
00:04:57,964 --> 00:05:01,718
I don't know. I still don't know.

47
00:05:03,386 --> 00:05:05,096
All those years ago.

48
00:05:11,978 --> 00:05:13,563
Okay, first things first.

49
00:05:13,647 --> 00:05:16,900
My name is Elton, not to be confused with...

50
00:05:16,983 --> 00:05:18,902
(ELTON JOHN PLAYING DANIEL)

51
00:05:18,985 --> 00:05:22,989
I left school, I got a job,
transport manager at Rita Logistics,

52
00:05:23,073 --> 00:05:27,536
modest little haulage company,
perfectly normal life, and then...

53
00:05:27,786 --> 00:05:29,996
it all went mad!

54
00:05:30,247 --> 00:05:33,708
ELTON: Two years ago I was in town,
I was stocking up,

55
00:05:33,792 --> 00:05:36,336
you know, nothing special,
all the usual stuff.

56
00:05:36,419 --> 00:05:38,171
When all of a sudden...

57
00:05:41,800 --> 00:05:44,344
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

58
00:05:47,430 --> 00:05:51,184
Shop-window dummies come to life.

59
00:06:00,944 --> 00:06:03,446
I survived, obviously.

60
00:06:03,989 --> 00:06:08,201
Twelve months later, I'm back in town.
I'm up West looking for a new suit,

61
00:06:08,285 --> 00:06:11,580
something nice and smart,
when I hear this plane overhead...

62
00:06:11,663 --> 00:06:14,249
(ENGINES ROARING)

63
00:06:22,924 --> 00:06:24,384
(BELL TOLLING)

64
00:06:25,802 --> 00:06:29,139
But it wasn't over yet.
'Cause then, Christmas Day.

65
00:06:29,222 --> 00:06:32,767
I'm in bed, fast asleep, nice and cosy,
7:45 in the morning,

66
00:06:32,851 --> 00:06:34,811
when all of a sudden...

67
00:06:37,314 --> 00:06:40,817
And I'm stuck in bed, all right,
'cause there's glass everywhere,

68
00:06:40,901 --> 00:06:42,402
and I was barefoot.

69
00:06:42,485 --> 00:06:45,155
I had to invent
this rudimentary pulley system

70
00:06:45,238 --> 00:06:49,034
Just to reach my boots,
and by the time I'd done that...

71
00:06:56,541 --> 00:07:01,087
And that's when it all started happening.
That's how I met Ursula.

72
00:07:01,171 --> 00:07:02,631
His name is the Doctor.

73
00:07:02,714 --> 00:07:05,467
-That's how I met Victor Kennedy.
-You stupid man!

74
00:07:05,550 --> 00:07:08,553
-That's how I met Jackie Tyler.
-You don't meet many Eltons.

75
00:07:08,637 --> 00:07:11,389
And that's how I finally met the Doctor.

76
00:07:12,349 --> 00:07:14,517
And realised the truth.

77
00:07:23,526 --> 00:07:27,030
I should say this isn't,
you know, my whole life.

78
00:07:27,113 --> 00:07:30,158
It's not all spaceships and stuff.

79
00:07:30,241 --> 00:07:34,663
'Cause I'm into all sorts of things.
I like football.

80
00:07:34,746 --> 00:07:38,291
I like a drink. I like Spain.

81
00:07:38,375 --> 00:07:42,003
And if there's one thing I really, really love,

82
00:07:42,087 --> 00:07:46,383
then it's Jeff Lynne
and the Electric Light Orchestra.

83
00:07:46,466 --> 00:07:48,802
'Cause you can't beat a bit of ELO.

84
00:07:48,885 --> 00:07:50,887
(MR BLUE SKY PLAYING)

85
00:08:12,075 --> 00:08:16,913
So, great big spaceship
hanging over London, imagine the theories.

86
00:08:16,997 --> 00:08:18,957
The internet went into meltdown.

87
00:08:20,375 --> 00:08:25,130
But I kept on digging.
Something was going on. Oh, yes.

88
00:08:25,213 --> 00:08:28,341
And then one day,
on some obscure little blog

89
00:08:28,425 --> 00:08:33,430
by someone called Ursula Blake.
It was, like, chance in a million.

90
00:08:35,432 --> 00:08:38,268
It was him, it was that man again.

91
00:08:38,393 --> 00:08:41,438
But the photo was new.
It was taken on Christmas Day,

92
00:08:41,563 --> 00:08:46,192
but Christmas just gone,
and he looked exactly the same.

93
00:08:46,443 --> 00:08:48,528
His name is the Doctor.

94
00:08:48,611 --> 00:08:51,322
-Doctor what?
-That's all anyone knows.

95
00:08:52,449 --> 00:08:55,577
At Christmas Day,
I was taking photos all over the place.

96
00:08:55,660 --> 00:08:59,706
I went mad with it all,
spaceships and lasers and everything.

97
00:08:59,789 --> 00:09:01,875
We all went to Trafalgar Square that night

98
00:09:01,958 --> 00:09:06,087
'cause everyone was celebrating
just being alive,

99
00:09:06,171 --> 00:09:09,758
and I snapped him in passing, that's all.
He was just some bloke.

100
00:09:09,841 --> 00:09:14,179
I didn't realise he was significant
until Mr Skinner pointed it out.

101
00:09:14,304 --> 00:09:16,056
Who's Mr Skinner?

102
00:09:16,765 --> 00:09:20,101
Oh, there's a few of us. The inner sanctum.

103
00:09:20,185 --> 00:09:22,479
All studying this Doctor.

104
00:09:24,022 --> 00:09:29,194
I've seen him, the Doctor, I swear to you.
I saw him when I was a kid.

105
00:09:29,277 --> 00:09:31,446
He was in my house and he was downstairs.

106
00:09:31,529 --> 00:09:35,075
Don't tell me, he looked
exactly the same then as he does now.

107
00:09:35,158 --> 00:09:37,994
Yes. Yes.

108
00:09:39,662 --> 00:09:42,999
Oh, my God, you believe me.

109
00:09:43,875 --> 00:09:45,335
I'm not the only one...

110
00:09:45,418 --> 00:09:48,880
ELTON: So that's how I met Ursula.
All thanks to the Doctor.

111
00:09:48,963 --> 00:09:53,176
Turns out we read all the same sites
and she only lived half a mile away.

112
00:09:53,301 --> 00:09:56,304
She was like a proper mate. Poor Ursula.

113
00:09:56,387 --> 00:09:58,515
(SCREAMING)

114
00:10:00,016 --> 00:10:03,394
But like she said,
there was this little community,

115
00:10:03,478 --> 00:10:07,398
the select few,
all with their stories of the Doctor.

116
00:10:07,482 --> 00:10:09,567
ELTON: This little gang used to meet up

117
00:10:09,692 --> 00:10:12,070
underneath the old library
on Maccateer Street.

118
00:10:12,195 --> 00:10:16,074
Mr Skinner, first name Colin,
but we always called him Mr Skinner.

119
00:10:16,199 --> 00:10:18,076
I don't know why, we just did.

120
00:10:18,159 --> 00:10:21,496
...to me, the Doctor isn't a man,

121
00:10:21,579 --> 00:10:24,415
he's more a collection of archetypes.

122
00:10:24,541 --> 00:10:26,000
ELTON: Then there was Bridget.

123
00:10:26,084 --> 00:10:28,545
...all these different Doctors come and go,

124
00:10:28,628 --> 00:10:32,257
but the single constant factor
is this faux police box.

125
00:10:32,382 --> 00:10:34,592
It keeps cropping up throughout history.

126
00:10:34,676 --> 00:10:36,386
She lived way up north,

127
00:10:36,511 --> 00:10:39,764
but she travelled down without fail
Just for the meetings.

128
00:10:39,889 --> 00:10:41,307
Then there was Bliss.

129
00:10:41,391 --> 00:10:45,728
What I'm trying to do
is sum up the Doctor. What he means to us.

130
00:10:45,812 --> 00:10:49,732
ELTON: She was ever so sweet Bliss.
Bless Bliss, we used to say.

131
00:10:49,816 --> 00:10:54,320
What he could represent
and what he should represent

132
00:10:54,404 --> 00:10:59,576
and what he never won't represent

133
00:11:00,285 --> 00:11:01,911
sort of thing.

134
00:11:02,662 --> 00:11:05,331
We should have a name.
You know, as a group.

135
00:11:05,415 --> 00:11:07,208
Names are very important.

136
00:11:07,292 --> 00:11:12,213
What we need is a good, strong name,
like a team. Something like...

137
00:11:13,089 --> 00:11:16,426
London Investigation 'N' Detective Agency.

138
00:11:16,843 --> 00:11:19,721
-LINDA for short.
-Say it again?

139
00:11:19,804 --> 00:11:23,975
London Investigation 'N' Detective Agency.

140
00:11:24,058 --> 00:11:25,768
_IINII?
-Fish 'n' chips.

141
00:11:25,852 --> 00:11:29,230
Rock 'n' roll. Chaka Demus 'n' Pliers.

142
00:11:29,355 --> 00:11:30,440
Ah!

143
00:11:30,523 --> 00:11:33,359
-LINDA, I like it. It's not too solemn.
- Ilike the 'N'...

144
00:11:33,443 --> 00:11:35,486
-We're the men from LINDA.
-And the women.

145
00:11:35,570 --> 00:11:36,821
LINDA united.

146
00:11:36,946 --> 00:11:38,781
Did you think of that on the spot?

147
00:11:38,865 --> 00:11:40,992
No, I've wanted to use it for years.

148
00:11:41,117 --> 00:11:43,036
I give you LINDA.

149
00:11:43,119 --> 00:11:44,662
ALL: LINDA!

150
00:11:44,746 --> 00:11:47,081
So we'd all meet up every week

151
00:11:47,165 --> 00:11:52,378
and we'd talk about the Doctor for a bit.
But after a while, Bridget started cooking.

152
00:11:52,462 --> 00:11:55,715
Oh, my God, that's gorgeous!
No, really. Wow.

153
00:11:55,798 --> 00:11:57,550
The rest of you, get your hands off!

154
00:11:57,634 --> 00:12:00,970
ELTON: Next thing you know,
Mr Skinner started his readings,

155
00:12:01,054 --> 00:12:02,805
'cause he was writing his own novel.

156
00:12:02,931 --> 00:12:06,517
SKINNER: "That's the last time you ride
the Ghost Train, Johnny Franzetta.

157
00:12:06,601 --> 00:12:09,103
"Now say your prayers!”

158
00:12:09,187 --> 00:12:10,813
To be continued.

159
00:12:10,939 --> 00:12:12,065
ALL: No!

160
00:12:12,148 --> 00:12:15,568
ELTON: Time went on. We got to know
each other better and better.

161
00:12:15,652 --> 00:12:19,822
I only started all this
because my daughter disappeared.

162
00:12:21,658 --> 00:12:26,746
But it wasn't aliens that took her away.
It was just drugs.

163
00:12:27,538 --> 00:12:32,502
I come down to London every week
and I just keep looking for her.

164
00:12:36,714 --> 00:12:38,424
Oh, Bridget.

165
00:12:40,760 --> 00:12:44,180
# I gave my love a chicken

166
00:12:44,305 --> 00:12:47,517
# It had no bone

167
00:12:49,143 --> 00:12:52,063
# I gave my love a cherry

168
00:12:52,146 --> 00:12:55,400
# It had no stone #

169
00:12:58,027 --> 00:13:00,863
# I've got a brand-new pair of roller skates

170
00:13:00,947 --> 00:13:03,074
# You've got a brand-new key #

171
00:13:03,199 --> 00:13:06,494
ELTON: Then it turned out
that Bridget could play the piano,

172
00:13:06,577 --> 00:13:08,663
and I confessed my love of ELO.

173
00:13:08,746 --> 00:13:11,416
Next thing you know, musical LINDA.

174
00:13:20,842 --> 00:13:24,887
# You got me running
Going out of my mind

175
00:13:25,054 --> 00:13:28,599
# You got me thinking
that I'm wasting my time

176
00:13:28,725 --> 00:13:30,727
# Don't bring me down #

177
00:13:31,227 --> 00:13:32,395
Just for fun.

178
00:13:32,520 --> 00:13:34,731
# Don't bring me down

179
00:13:34,856 --> 00:13:36,316
# Grroosss

180
00:13:36,441 --> 00:13:39,110
# Don't bring me down

181
00:13:39,235 --> 00:13:40,445
# Grroosss #

182
00:13:40,570 --> 00:13:42,030
You go.

183
00:13:42,155 --> 00:13:43,990
(INSTRUMENTS CLANGING)

184
00:13:44,073 --> 00:13:45,992
SKINNER: Now, careful. Mind the cables

185
00:13:59,964 --> 00:14:02,175
ELTON: And that's when it all changed.

186
00:14:02,258 --> 00:14:06,971
That Tuesday night in March.
That's when he arrived.

187
00:14:08,931 --> 00:14:10,308
Lights.

188
00:14:10,391 --> 00:14:13,061
ELTON: That's when we met
Victor Kennedy.

189
00:14:13,144 --> 00:14:16,105
And the golden age was gone.

190
00:14:16,189 --> 00:14:20,360
So, we meet at last, LINDA.

191
00:14:20,443 --> 00:14:22,862
Pleased to meet you, sir.
I'm sorry, was the music too loud?

192
00:14:22,945 --> 00:14:26,824
No, no, no. I don't shake hands.
Back, back. I suffer from a skin complaint.

193
00:14:26,949 --> 00:14:29,160
-Eczeema.
-Oh, you mean eczema.

194
00:14:29,243 --> 00:14:32,455
Oh, this is worse, much worse.
I blister to the touch.

195
00:14:32,538 --> 00:14:36,084
Back, back, all of you, further, further.
Thank you.

196
00:14:38,044 --> 00:14:42,632
Sorry, don't mind me asking,
but who are you?

197
00:14:42,715 --> 00:14:45,009
I am your salvation.

198
00:14:46,803 --> 00:14:49,347
URSULA: That's the Doctor.
ELTON: That's really him.

199
00:14:49,430 --> 00:14:54,519
Forgotten your purpose in life.
You, with your band and your cakes

200
00:14:54,602 --> 00:14:58,398
and your blubbing,
and all the while he still exists, the Doctor.

201
00:14:58,481 --> 00:15:00,108
Look at him. Just look!

202
00:15:00,191 --> 00:15:04,404
Move back, move back, all of you.
Hold on, wait for this bit.

203
00:15:04,487 --> 00:15:07,407
The picture cuts out,
but the sound still continues.

204
00:15:07,490 --> 00:15:09,325
Listen.

205
00:15:09,450 --> 00:15:11,661
Listen to the sound of the universe.

206
00:15:11,786 --> 00:15:13,830
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

207
00:15:13,913 --> 00:15:15,623
VICTOR: Yes.

208
00:15:19,001 --> 00:15:21,003
Oh, that's...

209
00:15:24,590 --> 00:15:27,260
-What is it? What's wrong?
-Leave him!

210
00:15:27,343 --> 00:15:29,637
You've heard it before, haven't you?

211
00:15:29,720 --> 00:15:32,974
When? When was it? Where?
Where were you?

212
00:15:33,224 --> 00:15:36,394
I'd forgotten. Till now.

213
00:15:38,020 --> 00:15:40,022
But it was that night.

214
00:15:40,690 --> 00:15:42,650
What night?

215
00:15:44,110 --> 00:15:46,154
I was just a kid.

216
00:15:47,029 --> 00:15:51,117
That's why I went downstairs,
it woke me up.

217
00:15:52,952 --> 00:15:54,245
That noise.

218
00:15:55,246 --> 00:15:57,748
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

219
00:16:00,126 --> 00:16:03,421
But what is it? What does it mean?

220
00:16:03,546 --> 00:16:07,008
That is the sound of his spaceship.

221
00:16:08,176 --> 00:16:10,678
VICTOR: Right then, homework!
Using the Torchwood files,

222
00:16:10,761 --> 00:16:14,182
we're able to look at all the old databases
in a completely new light.

223
00:16:14,265 --> 00:16:17,393
We're able to build up
a more detailed profile of the Doctor.

224
00:16:17,477 --> 00:16:21,272
I've allocated tasks to each of you.
I'd like you to...

225
00:16:21,397 --> 00:16:24,150
Careful, watch the eczeema.

226
00:16:24,233 --> 00:16:28,237
I would like you to complete your targets
and meet back here this time next week,

227
00:16:28,362 --> 00:16:30,907
one step closer to catching the Doctor.

228
00:16:30,990 --> 00:16:33,618
Well, don't just sit there! Move!

229
00:16:35,453 --> 00:16:38,122
Um, Bliss? It is Bliss, isn't it?

230
00:16:38,247 --> 00:16:39,665
-Yeah.
-Yes.

231
00:16:39,749 --> 00:16:42,168
Could I have a word with you
in private, please?

232
00:16:42,251 --> 00:16:44,921
-Course you can, yeah.
-Thank you.

233
00:16:45,755 --> 00:16:47,632
Goodbye, goodbye.

234
00:16:49,133 --> 00:16:51,886
ELTON: Better get to work. Lots to do.

235
00:16:51,969 --> 00:16:53,930
I never thought of it as work.

236
00:16:54,013 --> 00:16:57,475
It's what we've always wanted, though.
To find the Doctor.

237
00:16:57,558 --> 00:16:59,101
Yeah, I suppose.

238
00:16:59,268 --> 00:17:01,312
(BLISS SCREAMING)

239
00:17:01,812 --> 00:17:06,400
All of a sudden, without anyone saying so,
we were working for Victor Kennedy.

240
00:17:10,613 --> 00:17:15,743
ELTON: But we had to admit, he was right.
His methods were much more rigorous.

241
00:17:15,868 --> 00:17:20,039
It felt like we were getting
closer and closer to the Doctor.

242
00:17:20,122 --> 00:17:22,458
-Mr Kennedy?
-Yes.

243
00:17:22,750 --> 00:17:24,544
We were wondering...

244
00:17:24,627 --> 00:17:28,047
No sign of Bliss. Do you know where she is?

245
00:17:28,631 --> 00:17:31,884
Yes. Didn't she tell you?
She's getting married.

246
00:17:31,968 --> 00:17:35,972
She left a message.
It'll never last. Stupid girl.

247
00:17:36,681 --> 00:17:38,474
Come on, back to work!

248
00:17:39,308 --> 00:17:41,060
But we did get lucky once.

249
00:17:41,143 --> 00:17:44,522
A police box, newly arrived.
It says newly arrived today.

250
00:17:44,605 --> 00:17:46,065
It's in Woolwich.

251
00:17:46,857 --> 00:17:49,402
Well, don't just stand there!
Move! Move! Go! Go!

252
00:17:49,485 --> 00:17:52,113
But don't get excited.
That's where you came in.

253
00:17:53,114 --> 00:17:56,951
ELTON: Woolwich, police box,
red bucket blue bucket

254
00:17:57,034 --> 00:17:59,453
me so stupid, etcetera.

255
00:17:59,579 --> 00:18:01,706
-Useless!
-I just froze.

256
00:18:01,789 --> 00:18:03,249
You met him and you froze?

257
00:18:03,332 --> 00:18:05,876
-You stupid man!
-You can't hit me 'cause you don't touch.

258
00:18:05,960 --> 00:18:09,005
-You get a rash and an itch and everything.
-I can use this!

259
00:18:09,088 --> 00:18:12,466
Use that cane on him
and you'll get one hell of a smack off me.

260
00:18:12,592 --> 00:18:14,719
And then a good kick.

261
00:18:14,802 --> 00:18:18,514
Is that completely understood,
Mr Kennedy?

262
00:18:18,598 --> 00:18:20,391
Duly noted.

263
00:18:20,474 --> 00:18:25,646
Ursula Blake, most likely to fight back.

264
00:18:28,190 --> 00:18:32,903
Right then, we'll change tack.
We'll approach this sideways.

265
00:18:33,029 --> 00:18:35,740
If we're to discover the truth
about the Doctor,

266
00:18:35,823 --> 00:18:39,493
then we need to try and find her.

267
00:18:39,744 --> 00:18:41,871
VICTOR: Now, when it comes to
the Doctor's companion,

268
00:18:41,996 --> 00:18:44,165
the Torchwood files are strangely lacking.

269
00:18:44,248 --> 00:18:49,587
It seems the evidence has been corrupted,
something called Bad Wolf virus.

270
00:18:49,670 --> 00:18:51,756
At least we've got these photographs.

271
00:18:51,881 --> 00:18:53,924
They're first-hand evidence. Elton?

272
00:18:54,008 --> 00:18:57,887
It was a London accent, definitely.
She's from London.

273
00:18:57,970 --> 00:19:01,515
So we hit the streets. We get out there.
We take the photograph.

274
00:19:01,599 --> 00:19:03,351
Someone's got to know
who she is somewhere.

275
00:19:03,434 --> 00:19:08,439
But London's a big place. I should know,
my own daughter's out there.

276
00:19:08,522 --> 00:19:11,150
Bridget, don't make this personal.

277
00:19:11,233 --> 00:19:14,570
I don't like to be touched literally
or metaphorically, thank you very much.

278
00:19:14,695 --> 00:19:17,531
I haven't got the time.
Bleeding hearts, outside.

279
00:19:17,615 --> 00:19:21,869
Find me that girl! Go! Now! Move!

280
00:19:23,287 --> 00:19:26,582
ELTON: And so it began,
the impossible task.

281
00:19:26,666 --> 00:19:28,918
To scour the mean streets.

282
00:19:29,001 --> 00:19:32,421
To search a major capital city
for an unknown girl.

283
00:19:32,546 --> 00:19:36,634
To hunt down that face
in a seething metropolis of lost souls.

284
00:19:36,759 --> 00:19:39,595
To find that one girl in ten million.

285
00:19:39,679 --> 00:19:42,848
Oh, that's Rose Tyler.
She lives just down there.

286
00:19:42,932 --> 00:19:47,395
Bucknall House, number 48.
Her mother's Jackie Tyler.

287
00:19:47,478 --> 00:19:50,231
Nice family, bit odd.

288
00:19:54,610 --> 00:19:57,154
(MR BLUE SKY PLAYING)

289
00:20:02,118 --> 00:20:04,245
0i, Jackie!

290
00:20:04,745 --> 00:20:08,624
Hello, sweetheart. I'll see you
down the Spinning Wheel tonight, yeah?

291
00:20:08,708 --> 00:20:10,459
Pub quiz. Get them in!

292
00:20:10,543 --> 00:20:12,294
All right.

293
00:20:17,842 --> 00:20:20,052
ELTON: I'd been trained for this.

294
00:20:20,136 --> 00:20:24,390
Victor Kennedy's classes
covered basic surveillance and espionage.

295
00:20:24,473 --> 00:20:27,768
Step one, engage your target.

296
00:20:27,852 --> 00:20:30,980
Find some excuse to start a conversation.

297
00:20:31,105 --> 00:20:33,941
But how was I going to do this? How?

298
00:20:34,024 --> 00:20:38,112
Excuse me, luv, you couldn't give us a quid
for two fifties, could you?

299
00:20:38,195 --> 00:20:39,655
Yeah. Just...

300
00:20:42,950 --> 00:20:44,660
Oh, lovely. Cheers.

301
00:20:45,995 --> 00:20:49,206
Step two, without provoking suspicion,

302
00:20:49,331 --> 00:20:51,834
get on first-name terms with the target.

303
00:20:51,917 --> 00:20:55,004
My name's Jackie, by the way.

304
00:20:55,379 --> 00:20:56,630
I'm Elton.

305
00:20:56,714 --> 00:21:00,760
Oh, you don't meet many Eltons, do you?
Apart from the obvious.

306
00:21:03,554 --> 00:21:05,222
Step three,

307
00:21:05,347 --> 00:21:09,226
ingratiate yourself with a joke
or some humorous device.

308
00:21:09,310 --> 00:21:12,396
I tell you what, Elton.
Here we are complete strangers

309
00:21:12,480 --> 00:21:14,523
and I'm flashing you my knickers.

310
00:21:16,525 --> 00:21:19,069
ELTON: Step four, find some subtle way

311
00:21:19,195 --> 00:21:21,614
to integrate yourself
into the target's household.

312
00:21:21,697 --> 00:21:25,326
Mind you, I'm only down here
'cause my washing machine's knackered.

313
00:21:25,409 --> 00:21:29,038
I don't suppose you're any good
at fixing things, are you?

314
00:21:29,663 --> 00:21:32,750
Here we are. It was the fuse.

315
00:21:32,833 --> 00:21:37,213
There's nothing wrong with the machine.
That's fine, all working.

316
00:21:37,296 --> 00:21:39,924
Oh, Elton, I should have you on tap.

317
00:21:41,383 --> 00:21:44,762
I used to have this little mate
called Mickey, he did all that stuff.

318
00:21:44,845 --> 00:21:47,723
He's gone now, bless him.

319
00:21:47,848 --> 00:21:50,976
Well, if you need me, give us a call.
I'll jot down my number.

320
00:21:51,060 --> 00:21:53,020
You do that and I'll make us a cup of tea.

321
00:21:53,103 --> 00:21:54,855
Go on, go and sit down.

322
00:21:54,980 --> 00:21:58,067
Put the telly on if you want.
I can't bear it silent.

323
00:22:06,742 --> 00:22:09,829
JACKIE: It's just me these days,
rattling about.

324
00:22:09,912 --> 00:22:12,498
There's my daughter,
but she's gone travelling.

325
00:22:12,581 --> 00:22:14,792
I keep her bedroom
all nice and ready though,

326
00:22:14,917 --> 00:22:16,877
just in case she comes back.

327
00:22:17,002 --> 00:22:19,338
-And her name is?
-Rose.

328
00:22:21,257 --> 00:22:23,843
That's a nice name, Rose.

329
00:22:23,926 --> 00:22:27,263
-So, where is she travelling?
-All over.

330
00:22:27,471 --> 00:22:30,099
She's got her mobile.
I get a call now and then.

331
00:22:30,224 --> 00:22:31,851
Not as often as I'd like.

332
00:22:31,934 --> 00:22:35,479
Still, at that age,
who can be bothered phoning home?

333
00:22:35,563 --> 00:22:36,939
Yeah.

334
00:22:38,274 --> 00:22:40,359
Who's she with? Is it mates, is it? Or...

335
00:22:40,442 --> 00:22:43,279
Just mates, yeah.

336
00:22:45,406 --> 00:22:49,159
Well, if I had you
making a nice cup of tea like this,

337
00:22:49,243 --> 00:22:50,995
I wouldn't stray far from home.

338
00:22:51,078 --> 00:22:54,707
You're a charmer. Say it again.

339
00:22:56,959 --> 00:23:01,755
Magnificent! Oh, I could kiss you!
Except I can't, of course. The eczeema.

340
00:23:01,839 --> 00:23:05,050
-I've even got a picture of her on my phone.
-That's amazing.

341
00:23:05,134 --> 00:23:08,262
You've achieved steps one to four
in precise order. How did you manage it?

342
00:23:08,345 --> 00:23:11,181
I had to work very hard. She keeps
everything very close to her chest.

343
00:23:11,265 --> 00:23:12,725
That's a hell of a chest.

344
00:23:12,808 --> 00:23:15,811
But how do you move on?
Step five, that's the problem.

345
00:23:15,895 --> 00:23:17,980
Step five. That's this week's homework.

346
00:23:18,105 --> 00:23:20,482
I want a full plan of attack
from each of you.

347
00:23:20,608 --> 00:23:24,361
Now, go on! Vamoose! Avanti!
There's work to do.

348
00:23:26,030 --> 00:23:28,574
And, Elton, keep infiltrating.

349
00:23:28,657 --> 00:23:31,452
You will do anything to get
that information, boy, anything.

350
00:23:31,535 --> 00:23:33,162
Yes, sir.

351
00:23:34,538 --> 00:23:38,083
Oh... Oh, Bridget. Bridget? Oh, yes.

352
00:23:38,751 --> 00:23:41,629
Could I have a word with you
in private, please?

353
00:23:42,546 --> 00:23:44,173
Mr Skinner's giving me a lift.

354
00:23:44,298 --> 00:23:48,344
Oh, I can drop you at the station.
I'm sure Mr Skinner won't mind, will you?

355
00:23:48,469 --> 00:23:50,012
Not at all.

356
00:23:50,095 --> 00:23:53,390
-All right, Bridget, I'll see you next week.
-All right, then.

357
00:23:58,520 --> 00:24:00,189
Bye-bye.

358
00:24:00,272 --> 00:24:03,233
Now, Mr Skinner, I don't mean to pry,

359
00:24:03,317 --> 00:24:06,403
but did you give Bridget
a little kiss back there?

360
00:24:06,528 --> 00:24:08,280
I think I did.

361
00:24:08,364 --> 00:24:12,576
And if you get your way, might there be
more little kisses between the two of you?

362
00:24:12,701 --> 00:24:13,911
I think there might.

363
00:24:13,994 --> 00:24:15,663
-I knew it!
-That's brilliant.

364
00:24:15,746 --> 00:24:18,540
Now, let's not get excited. We'll see.

365
00:24:19,249 --> 00:24:21,418
(BRIDGET SCREAMING)

366
00:24:24,922 --> 00:24:28,300
ELTON: Infiltration went well
'cause Jackie kept phoning up,

367
00:24:28,384 --> 00:24:30,427
needing this and needing that.

368
00:24:30,511 --> 00:24:34,139
It was strange, the amount of things
that needed doing.

369
00:24:34,223 --> 00:24:36,183
It's like that flat was jinxed.

370
00:24:44,525 --> 00:24:47,653
It's weird, these fuses,
they keep on blowing.

371
00:24:47,736 --> 00:24:51,240
You must be near a substation
'cause then you get the power surges.

372
00:24:51,323 --> 00:24:54,410
Still, there we go. Fixed!

373
00:24:55,828 --> 00:24:59,957
Here we are.
A little reward for my favourite handyman.

374
00:25:00,082 --> 00:25:02,251
I shouldn't really, I've got the car outside.

375
00:25:02,376 --> 00:25:06,755
You could always splash out on a taxi,
or whatever.

376
00:25:08,257 --> 00:25:09,675
See what happens.

377
00:25:10,551 --> 00:25:11,635
Right.

378
00:25:12,469 --> 00:25:14,221
-Cheers.
-Cheers!

379
00:25:17,933 --> 00:25:22,146
-Very nice. What's that, French?
-I suppose so.

380
00:25:22,563 --> 00:25:25,858
They know how to do things, the French.

381
00:25:26,483 --> 00:25:29,403
Is it from Rose? I mean, is she in France?

382
00:25:29,486 --> 00:25:31,697
My daughter won't be coming back tonight,

383
00:25:31,780 --> 00:25:35,743
just in case you're wondering.
We've got the place to ourselves.

384
00:25:36,493 --> 00:25:37,619
Right.

385
00:25:41,999 --> 00:25:44,835
-Nice music.
-Il Divo.

386
00:25:44,960 --> 00:25:46,086
Yeah.

387
00:25:47,296 --> 00:25:50,591
You were saying... Power surges.

388
00:25:50,674 --> 00:25:54,219
-From the substation, yeah.
-Is that why it gets so hot in here?

389
00:25:54,303 --> 00:25:56,388
-Is it hot?
-Oh, I think so.

390
00:25:56,472 --> 00:25:58,599
-You should take your jacket off.
-No, I'm fine.

391
00:25:58,682 --> 00:26:00,642
No, look, you must be boiling.

392
00:26:00,726 --> 00:26:02,853
Oh, look at your shirt! Sorry!

393
00:26:02,978 --> 00:26:04,688
(STUTTERING) I'm fine, it's all right.

394
00:26:04,772 --> 00:26:06,940
-I've ruined it.
-No, honestly, it's fine.

395
00:26:07,024 --> 00:26:11,445
-Take it off, I'll put it in the wash.
-Oh, come on, it's only a little drop.

396
00:26:11,528 --> 00:26:13,113
Oops.

397
00:26:13,238 --> 00:26:14,907
There now.

398
00:26:14,990 --> 00:26:16,158
Ruined.

399
00:26:18,368 --> 00:26:21,872
ELTON: And there I was,
the ultimate step five.

400
00:26:21,955 --> 00:26:23,832
The perfect infiltration.

401
00:26:24,666 --> 00:26:27,336
Target, Jackie Tyler.

402
00:26:27,419 --> 00:26:28,545
Attaboy!

403
00:26:30,255 --> 00:26:34,176
You're right, it is a bit hot,
but it's about to get hotter.

404
00:26:34,259 --> 00:26:38,931
I'll see you soon. All right, be careful. Bye.

405
00:26:42,935 --> 00:26:46,063
-Everything all right?
-That was my daughter.

406
00:26:47,731 --> 00:26:52,736
Oh, look at you. I'm sorry.
I was just being stupid.

407
00:26:54,029 --> 00:26:56,532
-Is she okay?
-She's so far away.

408
00:26:57,616 --> 00:27:00,744
I get left here sometimes

409
00:27:01,954 --> 00:27:04,164
and I don't know where she is.

410
00:27:04,248 --> 00:27:07,126
Anything could be
happening to her, anything.

411
00:27:07,668 --> 00:27:09,878
And I just go a bit mad.

412
00:27:12,214 --> 00:27:14,341
Oh, put your shirt back on.

413
00:27:17,970 --> 00:27:19,555
Where is she?

414
00:27:19,638 --> 00:27:21,223
Doesn't matter.

415
00:27:22,933 --> 00:27:26,687
I'm sorry. You better go.

416
00:27:31,733 --> 00:27:33,777
Actually...

417
00:27:33,902 --> 00:27:37,072
ELTON: And that's when it struck me.

418
00:27:37,197 --> 00:27:40,325
Funny the things you think of
with your shirt off.

419
00:27:40,409 --> 00:27:43,912
But that's when I realised
what was really important.

420
00:27:44,621 --> 00:27:48,458
Never mind about Rose.
I'm not even gonna ask.

421
00:27:48,792 --> 00:27:51,003
And I will put my shirt back on

422
00:27:51,086 --> 00:27:54,089
because I'm gonna go out
and get us both a pizza.

423
00:27:54,173 --> 00:27:56,675
'Cause I reckon you need cheering up.

424
00:27:56,758 --> 00:27:59,845
She goes swanning off
and who's left to care about you, eh?

425
00:27:59,928 --> 00:28:03,390
So I say, nice bit of pizza.
We'll put the telly on nice and loud,

426
00:28:03,473 --> 00:28:07,477
we'll annoy that woman next door,
just you and me, as proper mates.

427
00:28:07,603 --> 00:28:10,105
Yeah? Mates.

428
00:28:10,189 --> 00:28:13,317
Go on, say yes.

429
00:28:14,735 --> 00:28:15,944
Yes.

430
00:28:18,697 --> 00:28:22,201
ELTON: All of a sudden,
a lot of things made sense.

431
00:28:22,284 --> 00:28:26,330
I'd got so lost in conspiracies
and aliens and targets,

432
00:28:26,455 --> 00:28:28,457
I'd been missing the obvious.

433
00:28:28,540 --> 00:28:30,334
'Cause I did like Jackie,

434
00:28:30,459 --> 00:28:33,295
but I liked someone else even more.

435
00:28:33,420 --> 00:28:36,089
(MR BLUE SKY PLAYING)

436
00:28:57,611 --> 00:29:02,991
Right. Let's get inside, then.
The pizza's getting cold.

437
00:29:03,075 --> 00:29:04,910
I went in your coat.

438
00:29:05,661 --> 00:29:09,331
For once in my life I thought, "I'll pay.”
I thought, "He's such a nice man,

439
00:29:09,456 --> 00:29:13,252
"he won't accept anything
so I'll just slip a tenner in his pocket.”

440
00:29:13,335 --> 00:29:15,003
And look what I found.

441
00:29:16,505 --> 00:29:18,590
A photograph of my daughter.

442
00:29:18,674 --> 00:29:21,009
No, no, no. It's not like that. I can explain.

443
00:29:21,093 --> 00:29:23,178
-I bet you can.
-I wasn't being pervy or anything.

444
00:29:23,303 --> 00:29:25,639
I wasn't after her.

445
00:29:25,722 --> 00:29:28,392
-I was looking for the Doctor.
-Oh, I know that.

446
00:29:28,475 --> 00:29:31,812
I worked that out.
'Cause it's never me, is it?

447
00:29:31,895 --> 00:29:34,064
No, but that's how it started,
but I changed my mind.

448
00:29:34,147 --> 00:29:36,233
Let me tell you something.

449
00:29:36,358 --> 00:29:41,196
About those who get left behind.
Because it's hard.

450
00:29:41,280 --> 00:29:43,573
And that's what you become, hard.

451
00:29:43,699 --> 00:29:48,578
But if there's one thing I've learnt,
it's that I will never let her down

452
00:29:49,204 --> 00:29:52,791
and I'll protect them both
until the end of my life.

453
00:29:52,874 --> 00:29:56,920
So whatever you want,
I'm warning you, back off.

454
00:29:57,004 --> 00:29:59,381
But, Jackie, I only wanted to meet him.

455
00:29:59,464 --> 00:30:01,466
-I thought you liked me.
-I do.

456
00:30:01,550 --> 00:30:04,803
Just get out of here! I said get out!

457
00:30:04,886 --> 00:30:07,014
And leave me alone!

458
00:30:15,397 --> 00:30:16,940
She was right. It's shameful.

459
00:30:17,065 --> 00:30:19,151
-We used that woman.
-I knew I couldn't trust you!

460
00:30:19,234 --> 00:30:22,404
You broke cover. You stupid little man,
you failed step five.

461
00:30:22,529 --> 00:30:24,948
I don't care about step five!

462
00:30:25,073 --> 00:30:29,077
'Cause it's all gone wrong, Mr Kennedy,
ever since you turned up.

463
00:30:29,703 --> 00:30:33,040
We used to come here every week
and we'd have a laugh.

464
00:30:34,291 --> 00:30:35,959
We were friends.

465
00:30:36,043 --> 00:30:39,296
No wonder they stopped coming.
I mean, there's no Bliss anymore,

466
00:30:39,379 --> 00:30:41,131
and even Bridget, she hasn't turned up.

467
00:30:41,256 --> 00:30:43,300
I've been phoning and phoning,
there's no reply.

468
00:30:43,383 --> 00:30:47,804
Who can blame her?
I'm sorry, Victor, but you're on your own,

469
00:30:47,929 --> 00:30:52,309
'cause I am leaving
and so are you, Mr Skinner.

470
00:30:53,352 --> 00:30:56,730
And as for you, Ursula,
you're coming with me.

471
00:30:56,813 --> 00:30:59,816
And we're going to the Golden Locust
and we're gonna have a Chinese.

472
00:30:59,900 --> 00:31:03,820
-What's that got to do with it?
-I mean, you and me. Together.

473
00:31:05,280 --> 00:31:08,533
Having a meal. If you want.

474
00:31:09,368 --> 00:31:12,371
Oh, I'd love it.

475
00:31:13,580 --> 00:31:15,415
But you can't leave.

476
00:31:15,499 --> 00:31:18,502
You'll never know
what he was doing, the Doctor.

477
00:31:18,585 --> 00:31:22,381
You'll never know what he was doing
in your house all those years ago.

478
00:31:22,464 --> 00:31:25,092
No, I'll never know.

479
00:31:28,303 --> 00:31:33,225
Ursula, get your stuff.
Mr Skinner, are you coming?

480
00:31:34,309 --> 00:31:37,396
Not to the Chinese if you don't mind.
Just sort of walking out.

481
00:31:37,479 --> 00:31:39,314
I certainly am.

482
00:31:40,649 --> 00:31:45,320
Victor, good luck. Goodbye.

483
00:31:46,905 --> 00:31:50,951
Mr Skinner, would you stay
for a minute, please?

484
00:31:51,034 --> 00:31:52,244
We're walking out.

485
00:31:52,327 --> 00:31:55,872
I've got numbers for Bridget.
I've kept records. I've got old numbers.

486
00:31:55,956 --> 00:31:59,459
We could track her down together,
you and I.

487
00:31:59,960 --> 00:32:02,587
That's more like the old team spirit.

488
00:32:02,671 --> 00:32:04,089
You two have a nice time.

489
00:32:04,172 --> 00:32:06,675
-I hope you find her.
-I'll email you.

490
00:32:08,844 --> 00:32:10,762
Just come a little closer.

491
00:32:13,890 --> 00:32:15,559
(SKINNER SCREAMING)

492
00:32:15,642 --> 00:32:17,519
-I love prawns. Crispy aromatic duck.
-Do you?

493
00:32:17,602 --> 00:32:19,271
Oh, I left my phone.

494
00:32:20,021 --> 00:32:21,857
-Really?
-Yeah.

495
00:32:21,940 --> 00:32:23,483
It's not in my pocket.

496
00:32:23,567 --> 00:32:25,527
-So much for the big exit.
-Yeah.

497
00:32:25,652 --> 00:32:27,404
Come on, hurry up.

498
00:32:34,369 --> 00:32:38,039
I'm not stopping, I just left my...phone.

499
00:32:39,541 --> 00:32:42,377
-Victor?
-Take your phone and go.

500
00:32:43,086 --> 00:32:45,046
Where's Mr Skinner?

501
00:32:45,380 --> 00:32:47,549
He's gone to the toilet.

502
00:32:48,550 --> 00:32:53,388
But we haven't got toilets,
we have to use the pub on the corner.

503
00:32:53,472 --> 00:32:55,557
Well, that's where he is, then.

504
00:32:55,724 --> 00:32:57,559
SKINNER: Help me!

505
00:32:59,728 --> 00:33:02,355
-What was that?
-It was nothing. It was nothing!

506
00:33:02,439 --> 00:33:04,524
SKINNER: Help me!
VICTOR: Shut up!

507
00:33:04,608 --> 00:33:06,151
That's Mr Skinner.

508
00:33:06,234 --> 00:33:09,738
Victor, look at your hands.

509
00:33:12,240 --> 00:33:15,285
VICTOR: (DISTORTED VOICE)
Look at the rest of me.

510
00:33:15,410 --> 00:33:20,499
You've dabbled with aliens,
now meet the genuine article.

511
00:33:20,832 --> 00:33:23,001
Oh, my God!

512
00:33:23,919 --> 00:33:27,422
-You're a thing.
-A thing?

513
00:33:27,631 --> 00:33:30,592
This thing is my true form.

514
00:33:30,759 --> 00:33:34,012
Better than that crude pink shape
you call a body.

515
00:33:34,095 --> 00:33:39,267
What happened? Where am 17
Ursula, is that you?

516
00:33:39,935 --> 00:33:43,605
That's Mr Skinner.
What have you done to him?

517
00:33:43,730 --> 00:33:45,649
I've absorbed him.

518
00:33:45,732 --> 00:33:49,277
-Colin? Is that you? Colin?
-Bridget, my love.

519
00:33:49,402 --> 00:33:52,072
Oh, my God! That's Bridget.

520
00:33:52,155 --> 00:33:56,618
-Colin, where are you?
-I'm here, Bridget. It's all right, I'm close.

521
00:33:56,743 --> 00:33:58,828
You've absorbed them both.

522
00:33:58,912 --> 00:34:01,206
What about Bliss? Where is she?

523
00:34:01,289 --> 00:34:02,999
(BLISS MUMBLING)

524
00:34:03,083 --> 00:34:04,209
What?

525
00:34:04,292 --> 00:34:07,128
BLISS: I said you really don't want to know.

526
00:34:07,254 --> 00:34:12,467
You've absorbed them.
You're some sort of absorb at hon!

527
00:34:13,009 --> 00:34:14,636
An absorbaling.

528
00:34:15,971 --> 00:34:19,099
-An Abzorbaloff.
-Yes, I like that.

529
00:34:19,182 --> 00:34:21,977
Let them go. I'm ordering you.

530
00:34:22,060 --> 00:34:26,815
-Let those people go.
-Oh, but they taste so sweet.

531
00:34:26,940 --> 00:34:30,652
Just think about the Doctor.
Ooh, how will he taste!

532
00:34:30,819 --> 00:34:34,197
All that experience, all that knowledge.

533
00:34:34,322 --> 00:34:38,577
And if I've got to absorb Jackie Tyler
to get to him, then so be it.

534
00:34:38,660 --> 00:34:40,579
Don't you dare!

535
00:34:41,830 --> 00:34:43,707
If I have to beat them out of you!

536
00:34:43,790 --> 00:34:46,459
Oh! Oh! No, no, please don't hit me!

537
00:34:46,543 --> 00:34:50,422
Look at me,
I'm such a slow and clumsy beast.

538
00:34:50,505 --> 00:34:52,591
Please don't hit me.

539
00:34:55,135 --> 00:34:57,804
Well, then. Give them back.

540
00:34:57,887 --> 00:35:00,515
What, you mean like this?

541
00:35:02,142 --> 00:35:05,228
Just one touch! That's all it takes!

542
00:35:09,024 --> 00:35:12,694
No. Oh, no, no.

543
00:35:12,777 --> 00:35:14,446
-No!
-No!

544
00:35:14,529 --> 00:35:16,865
-Leave her alone!
-Don't touch me.

545
00:35:16,948 --> 00:35:18,491
Oh, Elton.

546
00:35:18,575 --> 00:35:22,203
I'm so sorry you can't touch me.

547
00:35:22,495 --> 00:35:24,164
Ursula.

548
00:35:24,247 --> 00:35:27,375
Most likely to fight back indeed.

549
00:35:27,459 --> 00:35:28,793
Leave her alone!

550
00:35:28,877 --> 00:35:30,128
(SCREAMING)

551
00:35:43,808 --> 00:35:44,893
Yes!

552
00:35:44,976 --> 00:35:47,103
No, that's not fair!

553
00:35:48,229 --> 00:35:49,898
She tastes like chicken.

554
00:35:51,149 --> 00:35:52,859
Elton, where are you?

555
00:35:54,361 --> 00:35:58,156
Please. Mr Kennedy, please.

556
00:35:58,323 --> 00:36:00,533
I'm asking you.

557
00:36:00,617 --> 00:36:04,412
I'm begging you, give her back to me.

558
00:36:04,496 --> 00:36:06,081
I can't.

559
00:36:06,164 --> 00:36:09,959
Once they've been absorbed,
the process is irreversible.

560
00:36:10,794 --> 00:36:15,423
Wait a minute. Now I've been absorbed,
I can read his thoughts.

561
00:36:16,132 --> 00:36:20,220
Oh, my God! Elton, you're next.

562
00:36:20,303 --> 00:36:22,263
Get out of here.

563
00:36:22,347 --> 00:36:25,266
Now you've seen him, he can't let you go.

564
00:36:25,350 --> 00:36:30,021
Just run. Go on, never mind me. Get out!

565
00:36:30,105 --> 00:36:31,815
Isn't she the clever one?

566
00:36:31,898 --> 00:36:35,110
-Run, Elton! Run!
-Save yourself, boy!

567
00:36:35,193 --> 00:36:37,028
Run for your life!

568
00:36:37,112 --> 00:36:39,656
(BLISS MUMBLING)

569
00:36:40,407 --> 00:36:41,700
(GROWLING)

570
00:37:00,427 --> 00:37:04,514
Oh, what's the matter?
Have you given up so soon?

571
00:37:04,597 --> 00:37:08,184
There's no point. Where would I go?

572
00:37:09,853 --> 00:37:13,356
-Everything I ever wanted...
-Has been absorbed.

573
00:37:13,440 --> 00:37:15,650
Oh, Elton. Don't say that.

574
00:37:16,067 --> 00:37:21,072
-But it's true.
-Then join us. Join us, little man.

575
00:37:21,156 --> 00:37:22,490
Come on.

576
00:37:22,615 --> 00:37:26,161
It's everlasting peace. Come on, join us.

577
00:37:26,244 --> 00:37:28,079
Dissolve into me.

578
00:37:34,711 --> 00:37:36,254
(WHOOSHING)

579
00:37:50,518 --> 00:37:52,687
Someone wants a word with you.

580
00:37:55,523 --> 00:37:57,609
You upset my mum.

581
00:37:58,860 --> 00:38:01,696
A great big absorbing creature
from outer space

582
00:38:01,780 --> 00:38:05,074
-and you're having a go at me?
-No one upsets my mum.

583
00:38:05,200 --> 00:38:09,245
At last. The greatest feast of all,
the Doctor.

584
00:38:09,370 --> 00:38:12,874
Interesting. A sort of absorbatrix...

585
00:38:13,208 --> 00:38:16,961
-Absorbaklon... Abzorbaloff...
-Abzorbaloff, yes!

586
00:38:17,045 --> 00:38:20,215
Is it me or is he a bit Slitheen?

587
00:38:20,298 --> 00:38:24,135
-Not from Rexicoricophalvitorius, are you?
-No. I'm not that swine!

588
00:38:24,219 --> 00:38:27,514
I spit on them!
I was born on their twin planet.

589
00:38:27,597 --> 00:38:30,767
Really? What's the twin planet
of Rexicoricophalvitorius?

590
00:38:30,850 --> 00:38:32,560
-Clom.
-Clom?

591
00:38:32,685 --> 00:38:35,146
Clom. Yes, and I'll return there victorious,

592
00:38:35,230 --> 00:38:38,149
once I possess your travelling machine.

593
00:38:38,233 --> 00:38:40,652
-Well, that's never gonna happen.
-Oh, it will.

594
00:38:40,735 --> 00:38:45,240
You'll surrender yourself to me, Doctor,
or this one dies.

595
00:38:45,406 --> 00:38:49,994
You see, I've read about you, Doctor.
I've studied you. So passionate.

596
00:38:50,078 --> 00:38:54,499
So sweet.
You wouldn't let an innocent man die.

597
00:38:54,582 --> 00:38:58,545
And I'll absorb him
unless you give yourself to me.

598
00:39:01,297 --> 00:39:06,469
Sweet, maybe. Passionate, I suppose.
But don't ever mistake that for nice.

599
00:39:07,762 --> 00:39:09,764
Do what you want.

600
00:39:11,766 --> 00:39:14,269
-He'll die, Doctor.
-Go on, then.

601
00:39:18,106 --> 00:39:19,774
So be it.

602
00:39:19,858 --> 00:39:22,193
Mind you,
the others might have something to say.

603
00:39:22,277 --> 00:39:24,112
-Others?
-URSULA: He's right!

604
00:39:24,237 --> 00:39:27,073
The Doctor's right! We can't let him.

605
00:39:27,407 --> 00:39:29,367
Oh, Mr Skinner.

606
00:39:29,450 --> 00:39:33,788
-Bridget, pull! For God's sake, pull!
-No! No!

607
00:39:33,913 --> 00:39:36,875
If it's the last thing we ever do.

608
00:39:36,958 --> 00:39:40,295
Bliss! All of us, together, come on!

609
00:39:40,587 --> 00:39:44,757
-Pull! LINDA united!
-Stop it! Stop!

610
00:39:44,841 --> 00:39:46,634
Pull!

611
00:39:46,759 --> 00:39:48,511
(ALL GRUNTING)

612
00:39:50,805 --> 00:39:53,558
Elton! The cane, break it!

613
00:39:55,643 --> 00:39:59,147
My cane! You stupid man!

614
00:39:59,272 --> 00:40:00,648
(GROANING)

615
00:40:06,988 --> 00:40:10,825
-What did I do?
-The cane created a limitation field.

616
00:40:11,743 --> 00:40:16,581
Now it's broken, he can't stop.
The absorber is being absorbed.

617
00:40:16,664 --> 00:40:17,999
By what?

618
00:40:20,293 --> 00:40:21,669
By the Earth.

619
00:40:28,384 --> 00:40:30,011
URSULA: Bye-bye, Elton.

620
00:40:32,096 --> 00:40:33,681
Bye-bye.

621
00:40:42,231 --> 00:40:43,691
Who was she?

622
00:40:46,361 --> 00:40:48,029
That was Ursula.

623
00:40:58,164 --> 00:40:59,874
(SNIFFLING)

624
00:41:05,129 --> 00:41:07,340
And that's it.

625
00:41:08,257 --> 00:41:12,595
Almost. Because the Doctor
still had more to say.

626
00:41:12,679 --> 00:41:16,224
-You don't remember, do you?
-And then he explained.

627
00:41:16,349 --> 00:41:19,769
That night, all those years ago.

628
00:41:20,603 --> 00:41:23,564
There was a shadow in your house.

629
00:41:24,941 --> 00:41:27,860
DOCTOR: A living shadow in the darkness.

630
00:41:27,944 --> 00:41:31,280
An elemental shade that
had escaped from the Howling Halls.

631
00:41:31,990 --> 00:41:36,577
I stopped it,
but I wasn't in time to save her.

632
00:41:39,497 --> 00:41:40,748
I'm sorry.

633
00:41:47,088 --> 00:41:50,341
ELTON: Because that was the night
my mother died.

634
00:41:52,677 --> 00:41:55,263
(MR BLUE SKY CODA PLAYING)

635
00:42:31,966 --> 00:42:34,260
We forget because we must.

636
00:42:40,892 --> 00:42:42,977
So, there you go.

637
00:42:44,103 --> 00:42:46,773
Turns out
I've had the most terrible things happen,

638
00:42:46,856 --> 00:42:48,983
and the most brilliant things,

639
00:42:49,150 --> 00:42:52,820
and sometimes, well,
I can't tell the difference.

640
00:42:52,904 --> 00:42:57,241
They're all the same thing. They're just me.

641
00:42:57,325 --> 00:43:00,328
You know, Stephen King said once, he said,

642
00:43:00,411 --> 00:43:04,999
"Salvation and damnation
are the same thing."

643
00:43:05,083 --> 00:43:07,585
And I never knew what he meant.

644
00:43:08,503 --> 00:43:10,338
But I do now.

645
00:43:11,339 --> 00:43:15,760
'Cause the Doctor might be wonderful,
but thinking back,

646
00:43:15,843 --> 00:43:19,722
I was having such a special time,
just for a bit.

647
00:43:20,181 --> 00:43:22,141
I had this nice little gang.

648
00:43:22,225 --> 00:43:24,393
(DON'T BRING ME DOWN PLAYING)

649
00:43:26,020 --> 00:43:27,939
And they were destroyed.

650
00:43:28,731 --> 00:43:30,733
It's not his fault.

651
00:43:31,484 --> 00:43:34,612
But maybe that's what happens
if you touch the Doctor,

652
00:43:35,530 --> 00:43:37,657
even for a second.

653
00:43:39,283 --> 00:43:42,161
I keep thinking of Rose and Jackie,

654
00:43:42,245 --> 00:43:45,206
and how much longer
before they pay the price.

655
00:43:45,331 --> 00:43:47,834
URSULA: Oh, now don't get all miserable.

656
00:43:47,917 --> 00:43:51,295
-Come on, Elton. You've still got me.
-Oh, yeah.

657
00:43:52,964 --> 00:43:58,010
'Cause the Doctor said he could do
one last thing with his magic wand.

658
00:43:58,094 --> 00:44:02,807
If I can key into the absorption matrix
and separate the last victim.

659
00:44:02,890 --> 00:44:06,310
It's too late for total reconstruction, but...

660
00:44:06,602 --> 00:44:07,979
(BUBBLING)

661
00:44:08,062 --> 00:44:10,773
Elton! Fetch a spade!

662
00:44:10,898 --> 00:44:14,318
Even then, after all that,

663
00:44:14,402 --> 00:44:17,113
the Doctor saved me one last time.

664
00:44:20,575 --> 00:44:22,160
(GRUNTING)

665
00:44:24,662 --> 00:44:27,039
-Here she is.
-URSULA: Could be worse.

666
00:44:27,123 --> 00:44:32,170
At least I'll never age. And it really
is quite peaceful. You'd be surprised.

667
00:44:32,253 --> 00:44:37,049
It's a relationship of sorts. But we manage.

668
00:44:38,843 --> 00:44:42,430
-We've even got a bit of a love life.
-Oh, let's not go into that.

669
00:44:42,513 --> 00:44:45,224
And I don't care what anyone thinks,

670
00:44:46,184 --> 00:44:47,518
I love her.

671
00:44:48,311 --> 00:44:49,645
Oh.

672
00:44:52,356 --> 00:44:54,400
But the thing is...

673
00:44:55,610 --> 00:44:58,321
There you are,
I even bought a remote zoom.

674
00:45:00,531 --> 00:45:02,950
But what I wanted to say is,

675
00:45:04,076 --> 00:45:06,162
you know, when you're a kid,

676
00:45:06,287 --> 00:45:09,790
they tell you that it's all grow up, get a job,

677
00:45:09,916 --> 00:45:14,795
get married, get a house,
have a kid and that's it.

678
00:45:16,422 --> 00:45:18,257
(SIGHS)

679
00:45:18,341 --> 00:45:22,803
But the truth is,
the world is so much stranger than that.

680
00:45:23,554 --> 00:45:28,476
It's so much darker and so much madder.

681
00:45:31,145 --> 00:45:33,564
And so much better.

682
00:45:39,904 --> 00:45:42,323
-DOCTOR: 30th Olympiad.
-That's great!

683
00:45:42,448 --> 00:45:44,200
(CROWD CHEERING)

684
00:45:45,993 --> 00:45:47,995
-They're not safe.
-They're in the garden.

685
00:45:48,120 --> 00:45:49,997
WOMAN: Get them in, I'm begging you.

686
00:45:50,081 --> 00:45:53,084
In the last six days,
three of your children have been stolen.

687
00:45:56,045 --> 00:45:58,130
We need to find the source of that power.

688
00:45:58,214 --> 00:45:59,882
These? They're kids' pictures. Now get out!

689
00:46:00,007 --> 00:46:01,384
Chloe has a power.

690
00:46:01,509 --> 00:46:03,594
-She's using it to snatch the kids.
-Get out!

691
00:46:05,263 --> 00:46:06,764
If living things can become drawings,

692
00:46:06,847 --> 00:46:09,350
then maybe drawings
can become living things.

